Growing number of Chinese venturing through the jungle to seek asylum at the U.S.-Mexico border

By Edison Wu


A surprisingly growing number of Chinese citizens are crossing into the United States from Mexico every month, according to US Customs and Border Protection.

The journey is full of difficulties.


Crossing the deadly Darin Gap

These Chinese migrants first fly from China to Quito, the capital of Ecuador, where they do not need a visa to enter. Then they boarded a long-distance bus to Necocl, Colombia, before taking a boat to Darin Gap. It can take ten days or more to cross this 60 miles of dangerous jungle between Colombia and Panama.


The path through the jungle crosses wide rivers and mountains. Jungle snakes and robbers are also threating their lives. According to the International Organization for Migration (IOM), at least 141 people died and went missing when they were crossing the gap in 2022. The actual figure is likely to be much higher.


After crossing the Darin Gap, they still have to travel through Nicaragua, Honduras and Guatemala before finally reaching the U.S.-Mexico border.

Low chance of securing a U.S. visa

Flying to the U.S. on a tourist visa used to be the most popular way for Chinese asylum-seekers to stay in the U.S. However, this way has been largely closed off for the last few years.

Since FY 2015, the number of nonimmigrant visas issued to China has fallen dramatically.


The likelihood of obtaining a U.S. visa is even much lower for these Chinese asylum seekers, who generally have low incomes, education levels, and skills. As a result, jungle adventure has become an alternative method for them to go for the American dream.

Seeking Asylum

Once they cross into the United States from Mexico, they normally turn themselves in to border officials and seek asylum. Chinese citizens are more successful than people from other countries with their asylum claims in immigration court, according to the Transactional Records Access Clearinghouse, a data-research organization at Syracuse University.


In the past 20 years, the U.S. has always been the most popular choice among Chinese asylum-seekers, according to United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).

Fleeing authoritarian rule

There is no complete dataset collecting the reasons why Chinese citizens are seeking asylum. However, one factor is obvious - people are fleeing Xi Jinpings rule.

According to UNHCR, the number of Chinese asylum-seekers has skyrocketed since Xi took the power. The number of Chinese asylum-seekers in 2021 alone is higher than the total for the eight years from 2008 to 2012.


Whats Next

Once these new migrants get released from U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), they usually come to the homes of their relatives living in the U.S. Other than that, many head to New York City and Los Angeles, which are the two metropolitan areas with the largest Chinese populations in the United States, according to the American Community Survey.

Because of the language barrier, many of them started out spending their first few years in a small Chinese-speaking neighborhood, such as Flushing, Queens, the largest Chinatown in New York City. They usually secure jobs in Chinese restaurants or other businesses run by Chinese.

With worsening political persecution and a slow economy, more and more Chinese nationals are fleeing to the United States, Japan, Europe and other countries. This phenomenon has been coined the run philosophy in China. Many Chinese migrants even posted their run stories on Tiktok and YouTube. They also teach others how to trudge through the rainforest of Darin Gap.
